# Introduction

In physics literature, Lyapunov exponent is often referred to as the inverse localization length, and its positivity is often considered a manifestation of localization in a 1D system. At the same time, various physically desirable conclusions, such as e.g. the exponential decay of the two-point function at the ground state and positive temperatures with correlation length staying uniformly bounded as temperature goes to zero, are often implicitly assumed as attributes of localization. A way to derive them currently requires a strong form of dynamical localization : the exponential (in space) rate of decay of the two point function, that is $$\label{edl}
   {\mathbb E}\sum_s |\varphi_s(\ell)||\varphi_s (k)|
    \leq C e^{-\gamma |k - \ell|}$$ where $\{\varphi_s\}_s$ is a complete set of orthonormalized eigenfunctions (and the sum may be localized in energy, if needed).

In view of this, the *exponential decay rate in expectation* was defined in as $$\label{gamma1}
 \gamma_+ := \limsup_{k\to\infty}\left( -\frac{\ln {\mathbb E}(\sum_{s} |\varphi_s(0)|\cdot |\varphi_s (k)|)}{|k|}\right),$$ and $$\label{gamma2}
 \gamma_-:= \liminf_{k\to\infty}\left( -\frac{\ln {\mathbb E}(\sum_{s} |\varphi_s(0)|\cdot |\varphi_s (k)|)}{|k|}\right).$$ It is obviously connected to the minimal inverse correlation length. This definition can be localized to an energy range by summing over the eigenfunctions with energies falling in the range, in which case it is linked to the minimal inverse correlation length for Fermi energies falling in that range.

#  The lower bound

In this part we will prove the lower bound in Theorem <a href="#Maintheorem" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Maintheorem">1</a>: $\gamma_-\geq L.$ That is we will fix $\ell\in\mathbb{Z}$ and bound $$\int_0^{1} \sum_{s} |\phi_{\theta;s}(0) \phi_{\theta;s}(\ell)| d\theta=
  \sum_{n\in\mathbb{Z}} \int_0^{1}
   \sum_{n_{\theta;s}=n} |\phi_{\theta;s}(0) \phi_{\theta;s}(\ell)| d\theta$$ from above. By orthogonality, we have for any $s$, $$\label{Gauth1}
  \sum_{n} |\phi_{\theta;s}(n)|^2 = 1,$$ and for any $\theta\in \mathbb{Z}$ $$\label{Gauth2}
  \sum_{s} |\phi_{\theta;s}(n)|^2 = 1.$$ By symmetry, we can clearly assume that $\ell\geq 0$. We note that in order to prove the lower bound in Theorem <a href="#Maintheorem" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Maintheorem">1</a>, it suffices to show

<div id="Maintheoremupper" class="theorem">

**Theorem 4**. *Let $\lambda >1$, $\alpha$ Diophantine, and $0 < \Gamma < L$. Then for $\ell \geq 0$ large enough, we have $$\sum_{n\in\mathbb{Z}} \int_0^{1}
   \sum_{n_{\theta;s}=n} |\phi_{\theta;s}(0) \phi_{\theta;s}(\ell)| d\theta
    \leq e^{-\Gamma\ell}.$$*

</div>

For $n \in \mathbb{Z}$ and $0 < \eta < L$, we define the sets $$A_{\eta;n} = \{\theta:\quad \min_{|n^\prime|\leq 10|n|}
  |\sin\pi(2 \theta + \alpha (2 n + n^\prime))| \leq e^{-\eta |n|}\},$$ and $$B_{\eta;n;\ell} = \{\theta:\quad \min_{|n^\prime|\leq 10 |n-\ell|}
  |\sin\pi(2 \theta + \alpha (2 n + n^\prime))| \leq e^{-\eta |n - \ell|}\}$$ We clearly have that $|A_{\eta,n}|\leq (20|n|+1) e^{-\eta |n|}$ and $|B_{\eta;n;\ell}|\leq (20|n-\ell|+1)e^{-\eta|n-\ell|}$.

For $n \in \mathbb{Z}$ and $0 < \eta < L$, we define the sets $$A_{\eta;n} = \{\theta:\quad \min_{|n^\prime|\leq 10|n|}
  |\sin\pi(2 \theta + \alpha (2 n + n^\prime))| \leq e^{-\eta |n|}\},$$ and $$B_{\eta;n;\ell} = \{\theta:\quad \min_{|n^\prime|\leq 10 |n-\ell|}
  |\sin\pi(2 \theta + \alpha (2 n + n^\prime))| \leq e^{-\eta |n - \ell|}\}$$ We clearly have that $|A_{\eta,n}|\leq (20|n|+1) e^{-\eta |n|}$ and $|B_{\eta;n;\ell}|\leq (20|n-\ell|+1)e^{-\eta|n-\ell|}$.

By Theorem <a href="#Keytheorem" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Keytheorem">2</a> and Corollary <a href="#cornov18" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="cornov18">3</a>, we can obtain the following Lemma.

<div id="lem:ABeta" class="lemma">

**Lemma 5**. *For any $\eta\in(0,L-\varepsilon)$, the following estimates hold,*

1.  *For $\theta\notin A_{\eta;n}$ and $n_{\theta;s}=n$, we have $$|\phi_{\theta;s}(0)| \leq e^{-(L-\eta-\varepsilon) |n|}
        |\phi_{\theta;s}(n)|,$$ for large $|n|$.*

2.  *For $\theta\notin B_{\eta;n;\ell}$ and $n_{\theta;s}=n$, we have $$|\phi_{\theta;s}(\ell)| \leq e^{-(L-\eta-\varepsilon) |n-\ell|}
        |\phi_{\theta;s}(n)|,$$ for large $|n-\ell|$.*

</div>

<div class="proof">

\end{aligned}$$ Therefore, we have that for $t=e^{\eta n} e^{-(L-\varepsilon) n}$ and $\eta\in (0,L-2\varepsilon)$, $$\label{Glnew1}
  \{\theta\in\mathbb{T}:\quad \sum_{n_{\theta;s}=n}
 |\phi_{\theta;s}(0)\phi_{\theta;s}(\ell)|> t\}
 \subseteq A_{\eta;n}.$$ Let $t_1=e^{-\varepsilon n}$, $t_2=e^{-(L-2\varepsilon) n}$. Define $\eta(t)$ for $t_2\leq t\leq 1$ implicitly by $t=e^{\eta(t) n} \cdot e^{-(L-\varepsilon) n}$. Then for $t_2\leq t\leq 1$, $\eta(t)\geq \varepsilon$, and we have

$$\label{Gnov191}
     |A_{\eta(t);n}|\leq (20n+1)e^{-(L-\varepsilon) n}/t.$$ Since $\sum_{n_{\theta;s}=n} |\phi_{\theta;s}(0) \phi_{\theta;s}(\ell)|\leq 1$, for any Borel $\Omega\in \mathbb{T}$, we have $$\label{eq:layercake}
 \int_{\Omega} \sum_{n_{\theta;s}=n} |\phi_{\theta;s}(0)
  \phi_{\theta;s}(\ell)| d\theta =
   \int_{[0,1]}|\{\theta\in{\Omega}:\quad \sum_{n_{\theta;s}=n} |\phi_{\theta;s}(0)
    \phi_{\theta;s}(\ell)|> t\}| dt.$$ Thus we have $$\begin{aligned}
 %
   \int_0^{1} \sum_{n_{\theta;s}=n} |\phi_{\theta;s}(0)
   \phi_{\theta;s}(\ell)| d\theta &=& \int_0^{t_2} +\int_{t_2}^{t_1}+\int_{t_1}^1\nonumber\\
    &=& i+ii+iii .\label{Gnov192}

\end{aligned}$$ Then $$\label{Glnew2}
    i\leq t_2\leq e^{-(L-2\varepsilon) n}.$$ From <a href="#eq:layercake" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:layercake">[eq:layercake]</a>, <a href="#Glnew1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Glnew1">[Glnew1]</a> and <a href="#Gnov191" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Gnov191">[Gnov191]</a>, one has for large $n,$ $$\begin{aligned}
 %
   ii &\leq& \int_{t_2}^{t_1} |A_{\eta(t);n}| dt\nonumber \\
    &\leq& \int_{t_2}^{t_1}(20|n|+1)e^{-(\ln\lambda-\varepsilon) n}/t dt \nonumber\\
    &\leq& e^{-(L-2\varepsilon) n}.\label{Glnew3}

\end{aligned}$$ Noticing that $|A_{\eta(t_1);n}|\leq (20|n|+1)e^{-(\ln\lambda-2\varepsilon) n}$, one has $$\begin{aligned}
 %
   iii &\leq& (1-t_1) |A_{\eta(t_1);n}|\nonumber\\
   &\leq&  e^{-(L-3\varepsilon) n}.\label{Glnew4}

\end{aligned}$$ Thus, for $n\geq (1-\delta_0)\ell$, $$\int_0^{1} \sum_{n_{\theta;s}=n} |\phi_{\theta;s}(0)
   \phi_{\theta;s}(\ell)| d\theta \leq e^{-(L- 3 \varepsilon)n}.$$ Then, we have that $${\rm  I}  =\sum_{n=(1-\delta_0)\ell}^{\infty}
   \int_0^{1} \sum_{n_{\theta;s}=n} |\phi_{\theta;s}(0)
    \psi_{\theta;s}(\ell)| d\theta
     \leq  e^{-(L-4\varepsilon) (1-\delta_0) \ell}.$$ Similarly, $${\rm  II}
     \leq  e^{-(L-4\varepsilon) (1-\delta_0) \ell}.$$ Now we are in a position to estimate III. For $\theta\in[0,1]\setminus A_{\delta_0;n}\cup B_{\delta_0;n;\ell}$, by Lemma <a href="#lem:ABeta" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:ABeta">5</a> and <a href="#Gauth2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Gauth2">[Gauth2]</a>, one has $$\begin{aligned}
 %
    \sum_{n_{\theta;s}=n}|\phi_{\theta;s}(0)\phi_{\theta;s}(\ell)| &\leq&  e^{-(L-\delta_0-\varepsilon) \ell}   \sum_{n_{\theta;s}=n} |\phi_{\theta;s}(n)|^2 \\
    &\leq& e^{-(L-\delta_0-\varepsilon) \ell}.

\end{aligned}$$ It leads to $$\label{equ8}
 \sum_{\delta_0\ell\leq n\leq (1-\delta_0)\ell} \int_{[0,1]\backslash ( A_{\delta_0;n}\cup B_{\delta_0;n;\ell})} \sum_{n_{\theta;s}=n} |\phi_{\theta;s}(0)
   \phi_{\theta;s}(\ell)| d\theta\leq  e^{-(L-\delta_0-2\varepsilon) \ell}.$$ For $\theta\in A_{\delta_0;n}\cup B_{\delta_0;n;\ell}$, let $x_0(\theta)\in[-10\ell,10\ell]$ be such that $$|\sin\pi(2\theta+\alpha  x_0)|=\min_{|x|\leq 10\ell}
  |\sin\pi(2\theta+\alpha  x)|.$$ Notice that $x_0$ is unique by the fact that $\alpha$ satisfies Diophantine condition.

Let $$\Omega_1=\{\theta\in A_{\delta_0;n}\cup B_{\delta_0;n;\ell}| x_0(\theta)< n\},$$ and $$\Omega_2=\{\theta\in A_{\delta_0;n}\cup B_{\delta_0;n;\ell}| x_0(\theta)\geq n\}$$ By Theorem <a href="#Keytheorem" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Keytheorem">2</a> and the fact that $\delta_0\ell\leq n\leq (1-\delta_0)\ell$, for any $\theta\in \Omega_1$, $$|\phi_{\theta;s}(\ell)|\leq e^{-(L-\varepsilon)|\ell-n|}|\phi_{\theta;s}(n)|,$$ and for any $\theta\in \Omega_2$, $$|\phi_{\theta;s}(0)|\leq e^{-(L-\varepsilon)| n|}|\phi_{\theta;s}(n)|.$$

For $\theta\in\Omega_1\setminus A_{\eta;n}$ with $\delta_0<\eta<\ln L-\varepsilon$, by Lemma <a href="#lem:ABeta" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="lem:ABeta">5</a>, we have that $$\begin{aligned}
 %
   \sum_{n_{\theta;s}=n} |\phi_{\theta;s}(0)\phi_{\theta;s}(\ell)| &\leq&  e^{-(L-\varepsilon)|n-\ell|}
    e^{-(L-\eta-\varepsilon) |n|} \sum_{n_{\theta;s}=n} |\phi_{\theta;s}(n)|^2 \nonumber\\
     &\leq&  e^{-(L-\varepsilon)|n-\ell|}
     e^{-(L-\eta-\varepsilon) |n|} \nonumber\\
  &\leq& e^{-(L-\varepsilon) \ell}
      e^{\eta |n|}. \label{equ6}

\end{aligned}$$

A similar bound holds for $\theta\in  \Omega_2\setminus B_{\eta;n;\ell}$. That is, for $\theta\in  \Omega_2\setminus B_{\eta;n;\ell}$ and $\delta_0<\eta<L-\varepsilon$, $$\label{equ7}
  \sum_{n_{\theta;s}=n} |\phi_{\theta;s}(0)\phi_{\theta;s}(\ell)|
     \leq e^{-(L-\varepsilon) \ell}
      e^{\eta |n|}.$$ By (<a href="#equ6" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="equ6">[equ6]</a>), (<a href="#equ7" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="equ7">[equ7]</a>), <a href="#eq:layercake" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="eq:layercake">[eq:layercake]</a> and <a href="#Gnov191" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Gnov191">[Gnov191]</a>, we then have <a href="#Gnov192" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Gnov192">[Gnov192]</a> with $\int_0^1$ replaced by $\int_{\Omega_1\cup\Omega_2}$ and also <a href="#Glnew2" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Glnew2">[Glnew2]</a>, <a href="#Glnew3" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Glnew3">[Glnew3]</a>, <a href="#Glnew4" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Glnew4">[Glnew4]</a>. Thus we also have $$%
 \int_{\Omega_1\cup\Omega_2}\sum_{n_{\theta;s}=n} |\phi_{\theta;s}(0)\phi_{\theta;s}(\ell)|d\theta \leq e^{-(L-\varepsilon) \ell}.$$ It leads to $$\label{Gnov195}
 \sum_{\delta_0\ell\leq n\leq (1-\delta_0)\ell}\int_{\Omega_1\cup\Omega_2}\sum_{n_{\theta;s}=n} |\phi_{\theta;s}(0)\phi_{\theta;s}(\ell)|d\theta \leq e^{-(L-2\varepsilon) \ell}.$$ By (<a href="#equ8" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="equ8">[equ8]</a>) and <a href="#Gnov195" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Gnov195">[Gnov195]</a>, we get the bound of II, $${\rm II}\leq e^{-(L-\delta_0-3\varepsilon) \ell}.$$ Putting the bounds of I, II and III together, we have $$\sum_{n\in\mathbb{Z}} \int_0^{1}
   \sum_{n_{\theta;s}=n} |\phi_{\theta;s}(0) \phi_{\theta;s}(\ell)| d\theta \leq  e^{-(L-\delta_0-6\varepsilon) \ell}.$$ Letting $\delta_0,\varepsilon\to 0$, we obtain Theorem <a href="#Maintheoremupper" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Maintheoremupper">4</a>. ◻

</div>

# The upper bound

In this part we will prove the upper bound: $\gamma_+\leq L.$

<div id="thm:lowerbdd" class="theorem">

**Theorem 6**. *For any $\Gamma$ satisfying $L<\Gamma\leq 2L$, we have for $n$ large enough $$\ln \int_0^{1}  \sum_{s} |\phi_{\theta;s}(0) \phi_{\theta;s}( n)| d\theta
   \geq -\Gamma |n|.$$*

</div>

Fix $L<\Gamma\leq 2L$ and large $n$. Define sets $$\Theta _1=\{\theta\in[0,1]:\quad e^{-2\Gamma |n|}\leq |\sin\pi (2\theta+n\alpha)| \leq e^{-\Gamma |n|}\}$$ and $$\Theta _2=\{\theta\in[0,1]:\quad\text{ there exists some }  |k|\geq 1000|n| \text{ such that }|\sin\pi (2\theta+k\alpha)| \leq e^{- \frac{L}{100}|k|}\}.$$ Then $\Theta=\Theta _1\backslash \Theta_2$ has measure satisfying $|\Theta| \geq \frac{1}{100} e^{-\Gamma |n|}$.

<div class="lemma">

**Lemma 7**. *Let $\alpha$ be Diophantine with constants $\kappa,\tau>0$. Then for any $\theta\in\Theta$ and for any $m>C(\kappa,\tau) |n|$, $$\label{Gnov196}
    \min_{|x|\leq m}|\sin\pi(2\theta+x\alpha)|\geq e^{- \frac{L}{100}|m|}.$$*

</div>

<div class="proof">

*Proof.* Let $x_0$ be such that the minimum in <a href="#Gnov196" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Gnov196">[Gnov196]</a> is attained at $x=x_0$. We split our analysis into three cases depending on the value of $x_0$.

Case I. $|x_0|\geq  1000|n|$. Then the Lemma holds because of $\theta\notin \Theta_2$.

Case II. $|x_0|\leq 1000|n|$ and $x_0\neq n$. The Lemma holds because of $\theta\in \Theta_1$ and DC frequencies.

Case III. $x_0=n$. The Lemma holds because of $\theta\in \Theta_1$ (using $|\sin\pi (2\theta+n\alpha)|\geq e^{-2\Gamma |n|}$). ◻

</div>

It clearly suffices to show that for the eigenfunctions $\phi_s$ of $H = H_{\lambda,\alpha,\theta}$ (we ignore the dependence on $\theta$) we have $$\sum_s |\phi_s(0) \phi_s(n)| \geq\frac{1}{2}$$ as long as $|n|$ is large enough, uniformly in $\theta\in \Theta$. The first step is

<div id="prop:large" class="proposition">

**Proposition 8**. *For $|n|$ large enough and $\theta\in \Theta$, we have $$\sum_{|m|\leq C_{\star}|n|} \sum_{n_s = m} |\phi_s(0)|^2
    \geq \frac{1}{2},$$ where $C_{\star}=C(\kappa,\tau)$.*

</div>

<div class="proof">

*Proof.* Without loss of generality, assume $n\geq0$. Suppose $m\leq -C_{\star} n$ or $m\geq C_{\star}n$.

Using Corollary <a href="#cornov18" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="cornov18">3</a> with $n_{\theta;s}=m$, $\ell=0$, by <a href="#Gnov196" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Gnov196">[Gnov196]</a>, we have $$| \phi_s(0)|\leq  | \phi_s(m)| e^{-\frac{L}{2}|m|}.$$ Thus $$\begin{aligned}
%
  \sum_{|m|\geq C_{\star}n}  \sum_{n_s = m} |\phi_s(0)|^2&\leq &  \sum_{|m|\geq C_{\star}n} \sum_{n_s = m} | \phi_s(m)|^2 e^{-L|m|}\\
  &= &  \sum_{|m|\geq C_{\star}n} e^{-L|m|}  \sum_{n_s = m} | \phi_s(m)|^2\\
  &\leq & \sum_{|m|\geq C_{\star}n} e^{-L|m|}\\
  &\leq& \frac{1}{2}.
\end{aligned}$$ Combining with (<a href="#Gauth2" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Gauth2">[Gauth2]</a>), the result follows. ◻

</div>

The following lemma is similar to a statement appearing in with some modifications. We present a proof in the Appendix.

<div id="JS" class="lemma">

**Lemma 9**. *Suppose $$\label{gjs}
|\sin\pi (2\theta+n\alpha)| \leq e^{-\Gamma |n|}$$ with $L<\Gamma\leq 2L$. Suppose $\phi$ is an $\ell^2$ solution of $H_{\lambda,\alpha,\theta}\phi=E\phi$. Then $$\label{Gnov201}
    |\phi(n)-\phi(0)|\leq e^{-\frac{1}{2}(\Gamma-L-\varepsilon)|n|}||\phi||_{\ell^{\infty}(\mathbb{Z})}.$$*

</div>

<div class="proof">

***Proof of Theorem <a href="#thm:lowerbdd" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:lowerbdd">6</a>**.* For large $n$, by Proposition <a href="#prop:large" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="prop:large">8</a> and Lemma <a href="#JS" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="JS">9</a>, one has for $\theta\in \Theta$, $$\begin{aligned}
  \sum_{s} |\phi_s(0)  \phi_s(n)|
   &\geq \sum_{|m|\leq C_{\star}|n|} \sum_{n_s=m} |\phi_s(0) \phi_s(n)| \\
   &\geq \sum_{|m|\leq C_{\star}|n|} \sum_{n_s=m} |\phi_s(0)| (|\phi_s(0)| -  e^{-\frac{1}{2}(\Gamma-L-\varepsilon)|n|}||\phi_s||_{\ell^{\infty}(\mathbb{Z})}\\
   &\geq   \sum_{|m|\leq C_{\star}|n|} \sum_{n_s=m} |\phi_s(0)|^2-  e^{-\frac{1}{2}(\Gamma-L-\varepsilon)|n|}\sum_{|m|\leq C_{\star}|n|} \sum_{n_s=m} |\phi_s(0)|(\sum_{|k|\leq C_{\star}|n|}|\phi_s(k)|^2)^{\frac{1}{2}}\\
   &\geq \frac{1}{2}  - 2 e^{-\frac{1}{2}(\Gamma-L-\varepsilon)|n|}\sum_{|m|\leq C_{\star}|n|} \sum_{n_s=m} \sum_{|k|\leq C_{\star}|n|} |\phi_s(k)|^2\\
    &\geq \frac{1}{4}.

\end{aligned}$$ Then $$\begin{aligned}
 %
   \int_0^{1}  \sum_{s} |\phi_s(0) \phi_s( n)| d\theta &\geq& \int_{\Theta}  \sum_{s} |\phi_s(0) \phi_s( n)| d\theta \\
    &\geq& \frac{e^{-\Gamma|n|}}{400}.

\end{aligned}$$ This implies Theorem <a href="#thm:lowerbdd" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="thm:lowerbdd">6</a>. ◻

</div>

#  Proof of Theorem <a href="#Keytheorem" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Keytheorem">2</a>

By shifting the operator by $n_{\theta;s}$ units we can assume $n_{\theta;s}=0$. Without loss of generality, we assume $\ell>n_{\theta;s}$. Then in order to prove Theorem <a href="#Keytheorem" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Keytheorem">2</a>, it suffices to prove the following theorem.

<div id="Keytheoremsimple" class="theorem">

**Theorem 10**. *Let $\lambda>1$, $\alpha$ Diophantine, $n_{\theta;s}=0$, $\phi_s(0)=1$, $\ell\in\mathbb{Z}^{+}$. Let $x_0\in[-2\ell,2\ell]$ be such that $$|\sin\pi(2\theta+\alpha  x_0)|=\min_{|x|\leq 2\ell}
  |\sin\pi(2\theta+\alpha  x)|.$$ Then the following statements hold for large $\ell$:*

*If $x_0\in [-2\ell,0]$, then $$|\phi_s(\ell)|\leq
   e^{-(L -\varepsilon)\ell}.$$*

*If for $\eta\in(0,L-\varepsilon)$ $$\label{Gminnov18}
  \min_{|x|\leq 2\ell}
  |\sin\pi(2\theta+\alpha x)|>
    e^{-\eta  \ell},$$*

*and $x_0\in [0,2\ell]$, then $$\label{Gminnov181}
 |\phi_s (\ell)|\leq
   e^{-(L -\eta-\varepsilon) \ell}.$$*

</div>

Suppose $H_{\lambda,\alpha,\theta}\varphi=E\varphi$. Let $U^{\varphi}(y) =\left(\begin{array}{c}
                             \varphi(y)\\
                            \varphi({y-1})
                          \end{array}\right)$. It isa standard fact (e.g. (37) in ) that for large $|k_1-k_2|$, $$\label{G.new18app}
Ce^{-(L+\varepsilon)|k_1-k_2|}||U^{\varphi}(k_2)|| \leq  ||U^{\varphi}(k_1)||\leq  Ce^{(L+\varepsilon)|k_1-k_2|}||U^{\varphi}(k_2)||.$$

<div id="Keylemmaapp" class="lemma">

**Lemma 11**. *Let $r_{y}^{\varphi}=\max_{|\sigma|\leq 10 \gamma}|\varphi(y+\sigma k)|$. Suppose $k_0\in[-2Ck,2Ck]$ is such that $$|\sin\pi(2\theta+\alpha  k_0)|=\min_{|x|\leq 2 Ck}
  |\sin\pi(2\theta+\alpha  x)|,$$ where $C\geq1$ is a constant. Let $\gamma,\varepsilon$ be small positive constants. Let $y_1=0, y_2=k_0, y_3\in[-2Ck,2Ck]$. Assume $y$ lies in $[y_i,y_j]$ (i.e., $y\in [y_i,y_j]$)with $|y_i-y_j|\geq k$ and $y_s\notin [y_i,y_j]$, $s\neq i,j$. Suppose $|y_i|,|y_j|\leq Ck$ and $|y-y_i|\geq 10\gamma k$, $|y-y_j|\geq 10\gamma k$. Then for large enough $k$, $$\label{first}
  r^\varphi_y \leq\max\{ r_{y_i}^{\varphi}  \exp\{-(L- \varepsilon)(|y-y_i|-3\gamma k)\},
  r_{y_j}^{\varphi}\exp\{-(L- \varepsilon)(|y-y_j|-3\gamma k )\}\}.$$*

</div>

<div id="Keylemma1app" class="lemma">

**Lemma 12**. *Fix $0<t<L$. Suppose $$\label{ksmallG}
  |\sin\pi(2\theta+\alpha  k)|= e^{-t |k|}.$$ Then for large $|k|$ $$\label{Equ9}
 ||U^{\varphi}(k)||\leq \max\{ ||U^{\varphi}(0)||, ||U^{\varphi}(2k)|| \} e^{-(L -t-\varepsilon) |k|}.$$*

</div>

<div class="proof">

***Proof of Theorem <a href="#Keytheoremsimple" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Keytheoremsimple">10</a>**.* We start with the proof of Case I. Let $\varphi=\phi$, $\gamma=\varepsilon$, $k=\ell$, $C=1$, $k_0=x_0<0$ and $y_3=2\ell$ in Lemma <a href="#Keylemmaapp" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Keylemmaapp">11</a>. By Lemma <a href="#Keylemmaapp" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Keylemmaapp">11</a>, one has $\ell\in[y_1,y_3]$ and $y_2<y_1$, so $$\label{Gapp1}
    r^\phi_{\ell}\leq e^{-(L-C\varepsilon)\ell}  r^\phi_{0}+e^{-(L-C\varepsilon)\ell}  r^\phi_{2\ell}\leq e^{-(L-C\varepsilon)\ell},$$ since $|\phi(n)|\leq 1$ for all $n\in \mathbb{Z}$. By <a href="#G.new18app" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="G.new18app">[G.new18app]</a> and <a href="#Gapp1" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Gapp1">[Gapp1]</a>, we have $$|  \phi(\ell)|\leq e^{-(L-C\varepsilon)\ell}.$$ It finishes the proof of Case I.

Now weturn to Case II. Let $t$ be such that $tx_0=\eta\ell$. Let $\varphi=\phi$, $\gamma=\varepsilon$, $k=\ell$, $C=1$, $k_0=x_0>0$ and $y_3=2\ell$ in Lemma <a href="#Keylemmaapp" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Keylemmaapp">11</a>. By Lemma <a href="#Keylemmaapp" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Keylemmaapp">11</a> and <a href="#G.new18app" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="G.new18app">[G.new18app]</a>, one has (as in the proof of Case I), one has $$\label{Gapp3}
|  \phi(\ell)|\leq e^{-(L-\varepsilon)\ell}+e^{-(L-\varepsilon)|\ell-x_0|}||U^{\phi}(x_0)||.$$

Suppose $x_0\geq (\frac{\eta}{L}+\varepsilon)\ell$. In this case, by the definition of $t$, one has $0<t<L$. Let $k=x_0$ and $\varphi=\phi$ in Lemma <a href="#Keylemma1app" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Keylemma1app">12</a>, one has $$\label{Gapp4}
  ||U^{\phi}(x_0)||\leq \max\{ ||U^{\phi}(0)||, ||U^{\phi}(2x_0)|| \} e^{-(L -t-\varepsilon) x_0}\leq e^{-(L -t-\varepsilon) x_0}.$$ In this case, <a href="#Gminnov181" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Gminnov181">[Gminnov181]</a> follows from <a href="#Gapp3" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Gapp3">[Gapp3]</a> and <a href="#Gapp4" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Gapp4">[Gapp4]</a>.

Suppose $0\leq x_0\leq (\frac{\eta}{L}+\varepsilon)\ell$. In this case, <a href="#Gminnov181" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Gminnov181">[Gminnov181]</a> follows from <a href="#Gapp3" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Gapp3">[Gapp3]</a> directly since $||U^{\phi}(x_0)||\leq 2$. ◻

</div>

#  Proof of Lemma <a href="#JS" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="JS">9</a>

<div class="proof">

*Proof.* Without loss of generality, we assume $n>0$. Set $A= ||\phi||_{\ell^{\infty}(\mathbb{Z})}$. We let $\hat{\phi}(k)= \phi(n-k)$, $V(k)=2\lambda\cos2\pi(\theta+k\alpha)$ and $\hat{V}(k)=2\lambda\cos2\pi(\theta+(n-k)\alpha)$. Then by the assumption <a href="#gjs" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="gjs">[gjs]</a>, one has for all $k\in\mathbb{Z}$, $$\label{Eqpnew}
    |V(k)-\hat{V}(k)|\leq Ce^{-\Gamma n}.$$ We also have $$\label{Equnew}
 \phi(k+1)+\phi(k-1)+ V(k)\phi(k)=E\phi(k)$$ and $$\label{Equinew}
\hat{\phi}(k+1)+\hat{\phi}(k-1)+ \hat{V}(k)\tilde{\phi}(k)=E\hat{\phi}(k).$$ Let $W(n)=W(f,g)=f(n+1)g(n)-f(n)g(n+1)$ be the Wronskian. Let $$\hat{U}(k)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
                  \hat{\phi}(k) \\ \hat{\phi}(k-1)
                 \end{array}
   \right),$$ and $${U}(k)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
                  {\phi}(k) \\ {\phi}(k-1)
                 \end{array}
   \right).$$

By a standard calculation using (<a href="#Eqpnew" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Eqpnew">[Eqpnew]</a>), (<a href="#Equnew" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Equnew">[Equnew]</a>), (<a href="#Equinew" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Equinew">[Equinew]</a>) and palindromic arguments as in [^2], we have, $$\begin{aligned}
%
   |W(\phi,\hat{\phi})(k)-W(\phi,\hat{\phi})(k-1)| &\leq & |V(k)-\hat{V}(k)||\phi(k)\hat{\phi}(k)|  \nonumber \\
  &\leq &  C e^{-Ln}|\phi(k)\hat{\phi}(k)|\nonumber \\
  &\leq &  C A^2e^{-\Gamma n}\label{Gnov202} .  %
\end{aligned}$$ In Lemma <a href="#Keylemmaapp" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Keylemmaapp">11</a>, let $k_0=n$ and $y_3= 1000n$, then by <a href="#first" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="first">[first]</a> one has $$\label{Gnov203}
  |U(m-1)| , |U(m)|\leq e^{-\Gamma n} A,$$ where $m=500n$.

By <a href="#Gnov202" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Gnov202">[Gnov202]</a> and <a href="#Gnov203" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Gnov203">[Gnov203]</a>, we have $$\label{almostconstancyn}
       |W(\phi,\hat{\phi})(k)|
  \leq    A^2e^{-(\Gamma-\varepsilon)n},$$ for $|k|\leq 500n$.

Now we split $n$ into cases, depending on whether it is odd or even.

Case 1. $n$ is even. Let $m=\frac{n}{2}$, then $$U(m)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
                   \phi(m) \\ \phi(m-1)
                 \end{array}
   \right);
   \hat{U}(m)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
                   {\phi}( m) \\ {\phi}(m+1)
                 \end{array}
   \right).$$ Applying (<a href="#almostconstancyn" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="almostconstancyn">[almostconstancyn]</a>) with $k=m-1$, we have $$|\phi(m)||\phi(m+1)-\phi(m-1)|\leq  A^2e^{-(\Gamma-\varepsilon)n}.$$ This implies $$\label{Case11new}
    |\phi(m)|\leq   Ae^{-\frac{1}{2}(\Gamma-\varepsilon)n},$$ or $$\label{Case12new}
    |\phi(m+1)-\phi(m-1)|\leq   Ae^{-\frac{1}{2}(\Gamma-\varepsilon)n}.$$ If (<a href="#Case11new" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Case11new">[Case11new]</a>) holds, by (<a href="#Equnew" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Equnew">[Equnew]</a>), we also have $$\label{Case13new}
    |\phi(m+1)+\phi(m-1)|\leq  Ae^{-\frac{1}{2}(\Gamma-\varepsilon)n}.$$ Putting (<a href="#Case11new" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Case11new">[Case11new]</a>) and (<a href="#Case13new" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Case13new">[Case13new]</a>) together, we get $$\label{Phi1new}
    ||U(m)+\hat{U}(m)||\leq Ae^{-\frac{1}{2}(\Gamma-\varepsilon)n}.$$

If (<a href="#Case12new" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Case12new">[Case12new]</a>) holds, we have $$\label{Phi2new}
    ||U(m)-\hat{U}(m)||\leq  Ae^{-\frac{1}{2}(\Gamma-\varepsilon)n}.$$ Thus in case 1 there exists $\iota\in\{-1,1\}$ such that $$\label{Gnov197}
    ||U(m)+\iota\hat{U}(m)||\leq   Ae^{-\frac{1}{2}(\Gamma-\varepsilon)n}.$$ In Lemma <a href="#Keylemmaapp" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Keylemmaapp">11</a>, let $k_0=n$, $y_1=0$ and $y_3=m$, then by <a href="#G.new18app" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="G.new18app">[G.new18app]</a> one has, $$\label{half}
   ||\hat{U}(m) ||\leq A e^{-(L-\varepsilon)m}.$$

Let $T$ and $\hat{T}$ be the transfer matrices associated with potentials $V$ and $\hat{V}$, taking $U(m),\hat{U}(m)$ to $U(0),\hat{U}(0)$ correspondingly. By (<a href="#Eqpnew" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="Eqpnew">[Eqpnew]</a>), the usual uniform upper semi-continuity and telescoping, one has $$||T||, ||\hat{T}||\leq  e^{ (L +\varepsilon)m}.$$ and $$||T-\hat{T}||\leq  e^{ (L-2\Gamma+\varepsilon)m}.$$ Then by <a href="#Gnov197" data-reference-type="eqref" data-reference="Gnov197">[Gnov197]</a>, we have $$\begin{aligned}
  %
    %
   %
    %
   ||U(0)+\iota \hat{U}(0)||   &\leq &  || T||||U(m)+\iota\hat{U}(m)||+ ||T-\hat{T}|| ||\hat{U}(m) ||\\
      &\leq &  Ae^{ (L+\varepsilon)m}e^{-\frac{1}{2}(L-\varepsilon) n} + Ae^{ (L-2\Gamma+\varepsilon)m}e^{-m(L-\varepsilon) }.\\
       &\leq & Ae^{-\frac{1}{2}(\Gamma-L-\varepsilon)n}.

\end{aligned}$$ This completes the proof for even $n$ due to the definition of $U(0)$ and $\hat{U}(0)$.

Case 2. $n$ is odd. Let $\tilde{m}=\frac{N-1}{2}$, then $$U(\tilde{m}+1)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
                   \phi(\tilde{m}+1) \\ \phi(\tilde{m})
                 \end{array}
   \right);
   \hat{U}(\tilde{m}+1)=\left(\begin{array}{cc}
                   \phi( \tilde{m}) \\ \phi(\tilde{m}+1)
                 \end{array}
   \right).$$

Combining with (<a href="#almostconstancyn" data-reference-type="ref" data-reference="almostconstancyn">[almostconstancyn]</a>), we have $$|\phi(\tilde{m})+\phi(\tilde{m}+1)||\phi(\tilde{m})-\phi(\tilde{m}+1)|\leq  A^2 e^{- (\Gamma-\varepsilon) n}.$$ This implies $$%
   | \phi(\tilde{m})+\phi(\tilde{m}+1)|\leq   A e^{- \frac{1}{2}(\Gamma-\varepsilon) n},$$ or $$%
    |\phi(\tilde{m}+1)-\phi(\tilde{m})|\leq  A e^{- \frac{1}{2}(\Gamma-\varepsilon) n}.$$ Thus in case 2, there also exists $\iota\in\{-1,1\}$ such that $$%
    ||U(\tilde{m}+1)+\iota\hat{U}(\tilde{m}+1)||\leq A e^{- \frac{1}{2}(\Gamma-\varepsilon) n}.$$ The rest of the proof is the same as in case 1. ◻

